Medium: Ridge Plots

In Lab 2, you used side-by-side boxplots to visualize the distribution of weight within each species of rodent. Boxplots have substantial flaws, namely that they disguise distributions with multiple modes.

A âsuperiorâ alternative is the density plot. However, ggplot2 does not allow for side-by-side density plots using geom_density(). Instead, we will need to make use of the ggridges package to create side-by-side density (ridge) plots.

For this challenge you are to change your boxplots to ridge plots. You will need to install the ggridges package and explore the geom_density_ridges() function.

library(ggridges)
ggplot(surveys, aes(x = weight, y = species)) + geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.5) + geom_boxplot(outliers = FALSE) + labs(x = "Weight (grams)", y = "Species") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))
Picking joint bandwidth of 2.21

I read this for more information on the function : https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/ggridges/versions/0.5.6/topics/geom_density_ridges

# Medium: Ridge Plots

In Lab 2, you used side-by-side **boxplots** to visualize the distribution of 
weight within each species of rodent. Boxplots have [substantial flaws](https://www.data-to-viz.com/caveat/boxplot.html), namely that they
disguise distributions with multiple modes.

A "superior" alternative is the density plot. However, `ggplot2` does not allow
for side-by-side density plots using `geom_density()`. Instead, we will need to
make use of the `ggridges` package to create side-by-side density (ridge) plots.

> **For this challenge you are to change your boxplots to ridge plots. You will need to install the `ggridges` package and explore the `geom_density_ridges()` function.**

```{r}
library(ggridges)
```

```{r}
ggplot(surveys, aes(x = weight, y = species)) + geom_density_ridges(alpha = 0.5) + geom_boxplot(outliers = FALSE) + labs(x = "Weight (grams)", y = "Species") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))
```
I read this for more information on the function : https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/ggridges/versions/0.5.6/topics/geom_density_ridges
